WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.499 --> 00:00:02.950
My name is Daniel Donoghue.

00:00:02.950 --> 00:00:07.470
I'm a Professor of English,
and the Chair of the Committee

00:00:07.470 --> 00:00:08.405
on Medieval Studies.

00:00:12.090 --> 00:00:15.330
Diagrams are ubiquitous.

00:00:15.330 --> 00:00:17.400
There is the
mandala, for example,

00:00:17.400 --> 00:00:19.980
used in Buddhist meditation.

00:00:19.980 --> 00:00:23.610
Or the mandorla, used in
Byzantine and Western Christian

00:00:23.610 --> 00:00:25.890
iconography.

00:00:25.890 --> 00:00:28.350
But we don't have
to go so far afield.

00:00:28.350 --> 00:00:32.759
I can recall, for example, the
seductive symmetry of diagrams

00:00:32.759 --> 00:00:35.670
in textbooks from my earlier
school days in fields

00:00:35.670 --> 00:00:38.700
like geometry and biology.

00:00:38.700 --> 00:00:42.840
In more recent
decades, computers

00:00:42.840 --> 00:00:45.090
have allowed us to
turn many kinds of data

00:00:45.090 --> 00:00:49.060
into visual representations
of various kinds of data,

00:00:49.060 --> 00:00:51.880
including 3-D imaging.

00:00:51.880 --> 00:00:55.980
If we think of diagrams as
techniques of visualization

00:00:55.980 --> 00:00:59.160
that give order to knowledge
and perception, then

00:00:59.160 --> 00:01:03.450
the Middle Ages have a special
claim on our attention,

00:01:03.450 --> 00:01:07.680
because much of its
art is diagrammatic.

00:01:07.680 --> 00:01:11.700
We might be tempted to dismiss
diagrams as a convenience,

00:01:11.700 --> 00:01:14.340
perhaps visually
interesting, but still

00:01:14.340 --> 00:01:16.980
a tool that recedes into
the background behind more

00:01:16.980 --> 00:01:19.480
pressing questions.

00:01:19.480 --> 00:01:21.780
But as our talk this
evening will demonstrate,

00:01:21.780 --> 00:01:25.290
the topic opens into important
philosophical and aesthetic

00:01:25.290 --> 00:01:29.940
questions such as,
what is an image?

00:01:29.940 --> 00:01:32.370
Jeffrey Hamburger is the
Kuno Franke Professor

00:01:32.370 --> 00:01:34.770
of German Art and
Culture at the Department

00:01:34.770 --> 00:01:38.910
of the History of Art and
Architecture, here at Harvard.

00:01:38.910 --> 00:01:41.650
The recipient of grants
from numerous organizations,

00:01:41.650 --> 00:01:44.880
including the John S. Guggenheim
Foundation, the American

00:01:44.880 --> 00:01:49.380
Philosophical Society, the
NEH, and the Humboldt-Stiftung,

00:01:49.380 --> 00:01:52.170
Professor Hamburger
was elected a Fellow

00:01:52.170 --> 00:01:55.710
of the Medieval Academy
of America in 2001,

00:01:55.710 --> 00:01:58.620
and a member of the American
Academy of Arts and Sciences

00:01:58.620 --> 00:02:00.870
in 2009.

00:02:00.870 --> 00:02:05.880
He is the author, the co-author,
the editor and the co-editor,

00:02:05.880 --> 00:02:09.750
of too many books to list in
an introduction like this.

00:02:09.750 --> 00:02:14.580
So I will mention only
a few from recent years.

00:02:14.580 --> 00:02:16.980
I hope all of you had
the opportunity last year

00:02:16.980 --> 00:02:19.980
to visit the stunning exhibition
of medieval illuminated

00:02:19.980 --> 00:02:23.790
manuscripts, held in various
institutions in the Boston

00:02:23.790 --> 00:02:24.840
area.

00:02:24.840 --> 00:02:26.400
They were assembled
and displayed

00:02:26.400 --> 00:02:29.790
at the Isabella
Stewart Gardner Museum,

00:02:29.790 --> 00:02:33.120
at the McMullen Museum
of Boston College,

00:02:33.120 --> 00:02:36.600
and here at the
Houghton Library.

00:02:36.600 --> 00:02:39.850
Professor Hamburger was one of
the prime movers of the effort,

00:02:39.850 --> 00:02:42.870
and a co-editor of the
beautiful volume to accompany

00:02:42.870 --> 00:02:44.040
the exhibition--

00:02:44.040 --> 00:02:47.340
Beyond Words--
illuminated manuscripts

00:02:47.340 --> 00:02:50.280
in Boston Collections.

00:02:50.280 --> 00:02:53.550
Also in 2016, with
three collaborators,

00:02:53.550 --> 00:02:57.280
he produced Liturgical Life and
Latin Learning at Paradies Bei

00:02:57.280 --> 00:03:01.290
Soest, 1300-1425--

00:03:01.290 --> 00:03:03.720
Inscription and
Illumination and the Choir

00:03:03.720 --> 00:03:07.500
Books of a North German
Dominican Convent.

00:03:07.500 --> 00:03:11.610
In 2015, with Nigel Palmer,
he edited The Prayer Book

00:03:11.610 --> 00:03:12.790
of Ursula Begerin.

00:03:12.790 --> 00:03:18.300
And between 2015 and 2016, he
produced a 12-volume survey

00:03:18.300 --> 00:03:22.280
of masterpieces of book
illumination in central Europe.

00:03:22.280 --> 00:03:25.440
In 2016, with Harvard
University Press,

00:03:25.440 --> 00:03:28.050
he co-edited Sign and Design--

00:03:28.050 --> 00:03:32.110
Script as Image in
Cross-cultural Perspective,

00:03:32.110 --> 00:03:36.630
300 to 1600 CE.

00:03:36.630 --> 00:03:38.580
Next April, Professor
Hamburger is

00:03:38.580 --> 00:03:41.640
organizing a symposium
at Dumbarton Oaks,

00:03:41.640 --> 00:03:43.740
on the Diagram Paradigm--

00:03:43.740 --> 00:03:47.340
Byzantium, the Latin West,
and the Islamic World.

00:03:49.950 --> 00:03:52.650
As the Chair of the Committee
on Medieval Studies,

00:03:52.650 --> 00:03:55.680
I am constantly reminded
that to be a Medievalist

00:03:55.680 --> 00:03:58.320
means to be interdisciplinary.

00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:01.690
And that interdisciplinarity
is even more true,

00:04:01.690 --> 00:04:06.450
if that's possible, in the
field of Medieval Art History.

00:04:06.450 --> 00:04:09.060
Professor Hamburger's
scholarship

00:04:09.060 --> 00:04:13.800
moves with disarming ease among
various specialized fields,

00:04:13.800 --> 00:04:16.529
such as Late Medieval
Theology, including

00:04:16.529 --> 00:04:19.800
Mysticism, liturgy,
Latin and vernacular

00:04:19.800 --> 00:04:22.019
literature, and history--

00:04:22.019 --> 00:04:26.280
whether the micro-history of a
particular convent in Bavaria,

00:04:26.280 --> 00:04:29.430
or the particular interest in--

00:04:29.430 --> 00:04:31.260
or, I should say,
the broader movements

00:04:31.260 --> 00:04:34.950
of political and
cultural history.

00:04:34.950 --> 00:04:37.050
His work has shown a
particular interest

00:04:37.050 --> 00:04:40.740
in women's spirituality
and mysticism, especially

00:04:40.740 --> 00:04:43.440
in convents throughout
the German-speaking world,

00:04:43.440 --> 00:04:46.680
with special attention
to book illuminations.

00:04:46.680 --> 00:04:50.460
But his work is always
reaching toward big questions,

00:04:50.460 --> 00:04:53.220
so that when he examines
a particular instance

00:04:53.220 --> 00:04:57.660
of mystical art produced in a
Bavarian convent, for example,

00:04:57.660 --> 00:05:01.050
he crosses a threshold into
a much broader discussion

00:05:01.050 --> 00:05:05.940
of the paradoxical relationship
between art and mysticism.

00:05:05.940 --> 00:05:07.740
This evening, we are
going to be treated

00:05:07.740 --> 00:05:12.090
to a similar move, that opens
onto important questions facing

00:05:12.090 --> 00:05:13.620
us today.

00:05:13.620 --> 00:05:16.800
Finally, let me say, it is a
special pleasure for me to make

00:05:16.800 --> 00:05:19.740
this introduction, because
Jeffrey and I have been friends

00:05:19.740 --> 00:05:22.770
since our graduate school days.

00:05:22.770 --> 00:05:26.490
He will be speaking to us
on mind mapping, diagrams

00:05:26.490 --> 00:05:29.926
in the Middle Ages, and beyond.

00:05:29.926 --> 00:05:34.846
